\begin_layout Subsection
Giacomini-White test – doGWtest()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Giacomini-White (GW) test is a test on equal conditional predictive
 ability.
 Given that the population parameters are not known and must be estimated,
 it is the actual future loss that is of interest to the forecaster, rather
 than that based on some population value.
 The function doGWtest() implements two test approaches: (i) The unconditional
 test restricts attention to the forecast model whereas (ii) the conditional
 approach allows the evaluation of the 
\emph on
forecasting method
\emph default
, which includes the model, the estimation procedure and the possible choice
 of estimation window.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conditional test for forecasting performance tests whether the loss-differen
tial between two forecasts is conditional on current information, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The null hypothesis is then altered to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[d_{12,t+h|t}(\hat{\beta}_{1,t},\hat{\beta}_{2,t},y_{t+h})|z_{t}\right]=0
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the information set (in Gretl terms a list of potential variables) available
 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 In case the user selects the conditional approach, per default the lagged
 loss differential, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{12,t-h}$
\end_inset

, which is available in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $t+h$
\end_inset

 forecast, enters the information set.
 Additional conditioning variables may be included into the list 'z'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the moment we only support two loss functions, namely symmetric linear
 (V-shape) and symmetric quadratic (U-shape) loss but in principle other
 loss functions could be applied and may be incorporated into the package
 in future versions.
\end_layout

